4.2. Using RELAX, SysML and KAOS

4.2.1. Motivation

  • SAS autonomously modify their behavior

  • It is (more & more) difficult to self-adapt

  • Requirements tend to change

  • Gap: requirements / system model

4.2.2. Problem Statement

  • Difficult to anticipate all the states of SAS

  • Changing environmental conditions

  • Identify adaptable requirements

Requirements engineering languages must contain explicit constructs to deal with the uncertainty

4.2.3. Context of this work

  • Ph.D. Thesis (Manzoor Ahmad)

5. SysML

  • Unofficial date of birth: 2001!

  • First OMG spec: 19 september 2007

  • Actual Version: 1.3 (12/06/2012)

  • Who’s behind: OMG/UML + INCOSE

  • Main contributors :

    • Conrad Bock

    • Cris Kobryn

    • Sanford Friedenthal

5.1. SysML is…

A set of 9 types of diagrams

  • Structure

    • Block Definition Diagram (bdd)

    • Internal Block Definition (ibd)

    • Parametric Diagram (par)

    • Packages Diagram (pkg)

  • Behavior

    • Sequence Diagram (sd)

    • Activity Diagram (act)

    • Use Case Diagram (uc)

    • State machines (stm)

  • Requirements (req)

5.2. SysML is…

A UML profile

  • An extension. Example: bloc is a redefinition of class.

A notation

  • Growing interest in France (now at O’Level and in College)

5.3. SysML is not…

A method

  • SysML does not provide any particular method and is not attached to any process.

A tool

  • The tooling around SysML starts to be industrial.

6. Goal-based requirements

6.1. RELAX

  • Work initiated with Jon Whittle and Betty Cheng

  • Focus on SHALL statements

  • Hypothesis:

    • not always possible to achieve all SHALL statements

    • need to relax non critical requirements

  • RELAX

    • Designed specifically to capture uncertainty

    • Identifies two types of requirements:

      • Variant (or relaxable)

      • Invariant

6.2. RELAX syntax

6.3. RELAX semantics

  • Based on fuzzy branching temporal logic (FBTL)

6.4. Traditional reqs v/s Relaxed reqs

6.4.1. Traditional Requirements

6.4.2. Relaxed Requirements

6.5. RELAX Process

6.6. Domain Specific Language

  • Focuses on a particular domain (SAS)

  • DSL for RELAX to link requirements (RELAX) and system model

  • Xtext used for the development of this DSL

  • Xtext generates the editor for RELAX (called COOL)

6.7. COOL: the RELAX editor

6.8. RELAX Grammar

  • Grammar specifies the Meta Model and the concrete syntax for the DSL

  • Allows for the incremental development of the DSL

  • To Specify the grammar, Xtext grammar language is used

6.9. Code Generation

  • Code is automatically generated from the grammar

  • Right side shows the generated Sysml requirements

6.10. Generated Requirement Diagram

  • Non-functional requirements in textual format are transformed into graphical format with the help of RELAX grammar

6.11. Improvements needed

  • Help identifying relaxable reqs

  • Help organizing them

  • Help finding dependencies

  • Help liking reqs and model elements

6.12. Why GORE (Goal Oriented Requirements Engineering)?

  • SysML concepts for Requirements are not as extensive as in goal models

  • Allows detection and resolution of conflicts among requirements

  • Reasoning about alternative configurations

  • Trade off analysis

  • Help define relationships b/w requirements

6.13. SysML/KAOS Model

  • Extension of the SysML requirements model

  • Models both Functional and NF reqs

  • Consider requirements at the highest level of abstraction with a goal orientation

  • Impact of NF reqs on Functional ones

  • Traceability links between reqs and design

6.14. Extended SysML metamodel

6.15. SysML/KAOS Concepts

  • Contribution Goal

    • To satisfy an NFG

  • Contribution Association Class

    • Contribution Nature

      • Positive/Negative Contribution

    • Contribution Type

      • Direct/Indirect Contribution

6.16. Relationship b/w RELAX/SysML/Kaos

6.17. Current activity

  • SysML parametric diagrams from uncertainty factors ENV, MON and REL of RELAX

  • Correspondence b/w the SysML/Kaos and RELAX acts as a MM for our DSL

  • Use of formal methods

  • SysML Profile for Adaptive Systems (SPAS)

  • Need for empirical studies

  • We need case studies (from reqs to model)

8.1. Modeling Dimensions

8.1.1. General

  • What is the name of the modeling approach?

    • Relax/SysML/KAOS

  • Which documents?

    • Papers

8.1.2. Phase/Activity

  • During which software development phases is the modeling approach applicable?

    • Early requirements

    • Architecture/High-level design

  • In which software development activities is the modeling approach applicable?

    • Specification/Modeling

    • Evolution

    • Analysis

8.1.3. Language/notation

  • List the language(s) used by the modeling approach

    • RELAX, SysML, KAOS, UML

  • What is the standardization status of the language?

    • Only SysML/UML are OMG standards

  • For which application domains is the language applicable?

    • Self-Adaptive Systems

  • Which application domains should be avoided?

    • Application with invariants only

  • What are the paradigms supported by the language?

    • Object-Oriented

    • Goal-oriented

    • Component-based

  • The semantics of the language is:

    • Informal

  • What views are supported by the language?

    • Structural, Behavioral

  • What types of concrete syntax are used by the language?

    • Both Textual and Graphical
